<subsection xml:id="subsec-surface-area-of-frustums" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Surface Area of Frustums</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_zgz622c8">
             <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_qu0hh99k">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_h201jve4">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bytwz50v">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_cuk7knrq">
                        2.7 Surface Area
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_h01onht9">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_qklcfua8">
                        Explore the use of the surface area and volume of solids in real-life situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_9piycrdj" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_jnii5quh">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_9ep5b7vl" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_una0a19f">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <introduction xml:id="auto_uwhhtt21" component="lesson-plan">
            <p xml:id="auto_gjy8y4e9"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
            <ol>
                <li xml:id="auto_e9rl8eex">
                    <p xml:id="auto_sxw79kbn">
                        <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define a frustum as the shape formed when a cone or pyramid is cut parallel to its base, removing the top portion. Identify the properties: two circular bases, slant height, and height. State the formula: Total Surface Area <m>= \pi(R + r)\ell + \pi R^2 + \pi r^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_vzugvjkx">
                    <p xml:id="auto_u9ckuq18">
                        <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the total surface area of frustums using the formula. Find slant heights using the Pythagorean theorem. Use similarity to determine missing dimensions of a frustum.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_kjr3dkq5">
                    <p xml:id="auto_cpzzaoja">
                        <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving frustum surface areas such as buckets, lampshades, cups, and cooling towers. Determine material requirements for frustum-shaped objects.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_v870lohb">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/surface-area/surface-area-of-frustums.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_35mjyhss">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/surface-area/step-by-step-guide_surface-area-of-frustums.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_yuuej6ig">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_53boyvvj">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Groups of 3–4
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_hsw7yfoo">
            <alert>Activity:</alert> Modelling a Frustum Using Paper Cups or Cone Nets
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_r5bxwvuw">
            <alert>Teacher Prompts:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_uqqwb0oj"><p xml:id="auto_g7780rry"><q>What is a frustum?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_58gktrk0"><p xml:id="auto_5w723xcq"><q>What happens when you cut the top part of a cone parallel to the base?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5rl01bln"><p xml:id="auto_b03noj7l"><q>What surfaces make up a frustum?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_8ndv95vb"><p xml:id="auto_vxefdbqg"><q>What would happen to the surface area if the top radius increased?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_m5rw80ds"><p xml:id="auto_ry2bc1zc"><q>Why is it necessary to measure the slant height, not the vertical height?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tr9foat3"><p xml:id="auto_70n51vkf"><q>Can you find any real-life objects shaped like a frustum?</q></p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_qrmvlv15">
            <alert>Teacher Role During Discovery:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_dizltfbq"><p xml:id="auto_cirtsyh9">Circulate among groups, ensuring students understand how to cut and assemble the frustum.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zadp684i"><p xml:id="auto_y229mrj1">Ask probing questions: <q>What surfaces do you see? How can we find the area of each surface?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_n4hbqljd"><p xml:id="auto_r0k8nt5j">For struggling groups: <q>Let us start by finding the area of the bottom base. Then find the area of the top base. What about the curved surface?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3wo2w9wt"><p xml:id="auto_2yrrokyb">For early finishers: <q>Given a full cone, how much surface area is lost when the top is cut off?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ards22w8"><p xml:id="auto_ukh4y5q3">Identify 2–3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>



    <activity xml:id="auto_oecrrf2w">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_m5bxed8d">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_gak37leu">
              Modelling a frustum using a paper cup or cone-shaped fruit juice glass and calculate its surface area.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_3yvlurb6">
                <m>\textbf{ Materials needed:}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_bjv9hzkz">
                <ul xml:id="auto_s1crebpj">
                    <li xml:id="auto_d4e55sxu">
                        <p xml:id="auto_rci9wau8">
                           Printable nets of a cone (to cut and create a frustum)
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_7dhhugds">
                             Rulers or measuring tape
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_j7m2t4kl">
                            Scissors

                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_201zpzzk">
                            
                             Tape or glue
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_p3mvuher">
                             Formula sheet
                         </p>
                         <p xml:id="auto_6x8932av">
                             Worksheets for sketching and calculations 
                         </p>
                       
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ojzzvowc">
                        <p xml:id="auto_bdxqvqg1">
                            A  frustum is formed when the top part of a cone is cut off parallel to the base.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_upg6vkma">
                        <p xml:id="auto_axmdoia5">
                            Surface area includes:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_ypgfetz1">
                           <m>\textbf{Curved surface area}</m> (side)
                         </p> 
                         <p xml:id="auto_28xy0nfd"> 
                           <m>\textbf{Area of both circular bases}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_tohzztkc">
                        <p xml:id="auto_watu4x1q">
                             Build the Frustum Model.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_51gng2v7">
                             Take the cone net and cut off the top part (smaller cone) parallel to the base.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_mjc7572b">
                             Assemble the remaining portion to form a frustum
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_416tkh7g">
                          Alternatively, use actual paper/plastic cups and measure directly
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_11n70cn6">
                        <p xml:id="auto_wqkr5aew">
                             Label Dimensions
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_u34tvhly">
                             Radius of the larger base (R)
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_z1h7uy49">    
                             Radius of the smaller top base (r)
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_73eikfrz">    

                             Slant height (l) of the frustum
                        </p>   
                        <p xml:id="auto_xytm50cj"> 
                             (If not provided, measure the height and use the Pythagorean theorem)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_xu7t3fa8">
                        <p xml:id="auto_miftf093">
                            Calculate Surface Area
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_u94z45r4">
                        <p xml:id="auto_0dx29v6d">
                             Use the surface area formula:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_m4m9xuut">
                             Total Surface Area = <m>\pi (R+r)\ell + \pi R^2 + \pi r^2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_pypvi57r">
                        <p xml:id="auto_9r3a64me">
                             <m>\pi(R+r)</m>l: Curved surface
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_y52196nf">
                            <m> \pi R^2</m>: Area of bottom base
                         
                            </p>
                         <p xml:id="auto_jlbppa4l">
                           <m>\pi r^2</m>: Area of top base
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_vyxsl2nl">
                        <p xml:id="auto_sd9leb2p">
                            Example: Given Top radius (r): 3 cm , Bottom radius (R): 5 cm and Slant height (l): 6 cm
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_j8fzdvxv">

                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Surface Area } =\amp \pi(5\, \text {cm}+3\, \text {cm})(6\, \text {cm}) + \pi(5\, \text {cm})^2 + \pi(3\, \text {cm})^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp  3.14 \times (8\, \text {cm})\times(6\, \text {cm}) + 3.14 \times 25\, \text {cm} + 3.14 \times 9\, \text {cm}</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp (3.14 \times \, 48 \text {cm} ) \times(3.14 \times \, 25 \text {cm} )  \times(3.14 \times \, 9 \text {cm} )  </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 150.72 \, \text{cm}^2 + 78.50 \, \text{cm}^2 + 28.26\, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp257.48\, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_d80v2tjq">
                        <p xml:id="auto_gb60m00i">
                            <m>\textbf{Study Questions}.</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_0uhan0yk">
                             What would happen to the surface area if the top radius increased?
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_ydoz8oi0">
                            Why is it necessary to measure the slant height, not the vertical height?
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_p5spt2l4">
                            Can you find any real-life objects shaped like a frustum?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_v28wglhg">
                        <p xml:id="auto_ek8ds4sd">
                            <m>\textbf{Assignment}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_8t4c0udn">
                            Design their own frustum cups with chosen dimensions.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_trw9ckpm">
                        <p xml:id="auto_uaarmssx">
                            Given a full cone, how much surface area is “lost” when the top is cut off?
                        </p>
                    </li>
    
                </ul>
            </p>
        </statement>

    </activity>
 <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_dltjngow">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_8f5pc50v">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Whole class
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_bro8h512">
            <alert>Teacher Guidance:</alert> After students have completed the anchor activity and shared their findings, formalise the formula for finding the surface area of a frustum. Direct learners' attention to the Key Takeaway box above.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_7o97t8n9">
            <alert>Prompting Questions:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_xvasoyi0"><p xml:id="auto_v6u6r8xe"><q>What is the difference between a frustum and a cone?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_cv2nrsdh"><p xml:id="auto_742k8ufe"><q>Do I only need the curved surface area?</q> (No — you must add both circular bases.)</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_strlpoog"><p xml:id="auto_lvgjjp18"><q>Are the slant height and vertical height the same?</q> (No — the slant height is along the side.)</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_m3f3to7z"><p xml:id="auto_10ge4rdc"><q>Can I use the cone formula directly for a frustum?</q> (No — a frustum has two bases.)</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <insight xml:id="auto_a1o0qa2v">
        <p xml:id="auto_t2r3m5af">
            A frustum is a cone or pyramid is cut parallel to its base, removing the top portion. This results in a truncated shape with two parallel bases one smaller than the other e.g a lampshades, Truncated cones in engineering, buckets, Tunnels, Cooling towers in power plants etc
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_vimjgh2r">
            <ul xml:id="auto_1o1wckou">
                <li xml:id="auto_6mibtwxg">
                    <p xml:id="auto_3qg346u9">
                        Thereby a frustum is the portion of a cone (or pyramid) that remains after the top part is cut off parallel to the base.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_25nnvmxq">
                        <m>\textbf{Properties of a Frustum}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_i7lwdj43">
                    <p xml:id="auto_t0ftonj2">
                        Two Circular Bases - A frustum has a larger base and a smaller base (both circular).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_w4ku90lv">
                    <p xml:id="auto_73y57b2f">
                    Slant Height <m>\ell</m>. The distance between the two bases along the side of the frustum. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_h0431rac">
                    <p xml:id="auto_tp2btpkf">
                        Height <m>h</m> - The vertical distance between the two bases.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_uzs39hbu">
                    <p xml:id="auto_n9u8u11s">
                        Curved Surface Area (CSA) - The side surface that connects the two bases.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2x651fng">
                    <p xml:id="auto_oaedynaw">
                        Total Surface Area (TSA) - The sum of the CSA and the areas of the two circular bases.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3e0k4bft">
                    <p xml:id="auto_z3uqppld">
                        <m>\textbf{NOTE:}</m> Volume, the space inside the frustum, is calculated using a formula derived from a full cone.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_n0g1wrua">
            <m>\textbf{Types of frustums}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_gd9z6pua">
        <m>\textbf{Full cone}</m> 
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_3dr7l1t4">
            Important formulas to note;
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_50k7uswf">
            <ol xml:id="auto_ahufmt28">
                <li xml:id="auto_01p9hcpw">
                    <p xml:id="auto_6b7q7ias">
                        Slant Height <m>\ell</m>
                        <me>
                            \ell = \sqrt{(H+h)^2 + R^2}
                        </me>
                        
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_0m2rt2or">
                    <p xml:id="auto_ao26trhs">
                        Curved Surface Area (CSA)
                        <me>
                            CSA = \pi\, RL  \,\text{and}  \pi\, rl \, \text{for the smaller cone}
                        </me>
                        
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_dbwfo1s5">
                    <p xml:id="auto_by2tzvlb">
                        3. Total Surface Area (TSA)
                        <me>
                            \pi RL + \pi rl
                        </me>
                        
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- <axiom component="lesson-plan">
