        </p>
    </axiom> -->

    <!-- <p xml:id="auto_214uny0x">
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p> -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_fxd3wohs">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_9bs2k5w9">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Individual, then pairs to compare
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_9r9phlr7">
            <alert>Teacher Guidance:</alert> Walk learners through the worked examples that follow. The first example uses similarity to complete a cone before calculating. Encourage learners to attempt the second example independently before revealing the solution.
        </p>
    </axiom>

          <example xml:id="auto_vx4a9xrm">
        <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_dxoz8g3r">
                    Find the surface area of the galvanized iron bucket below.
                </p>
             <image width="40%">
        <latex-image label="frustum-galvanised-iron-bucket">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                  % Define a light purple color
                    \definecolor{lightpurple}{RGB}{230,230,250}
                    
                    % Bottom ellipse (full width)
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) ellipse (4 and 2);
                    \fill[lightpurple, opacity=0.7] (0,0) ellipse (4 and 2);
                    
                    % Top ellipse (narrower)
                    \draw[thick] (0,5) ellipse (2 and 1);
                    \fill[lightpurple, opacity=0.7] (0,5) ellipse (2 and 1);
                    
                    % Side surfaces
                    \fill[lightpurple, opacity=0.5] 
                        (-4,0) -- (-2,5) -- (2,5) -- (4,0) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Outline of side lines
                    \draw[thick] (-4,0) -- (-2,5);
                    \draw[thick] (4,0) -- (2,5);
                    \draw[thick] (-4,0) -- (4,0);
                    \draw[thick] (-2,5) -- (2,5);
                    
                    % Height line (dashed)
                    \draw[dashed, blue] (0,0) -- (0,5);
                    
                    % Dimension lines and labels
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-4.5,0) -- node[left] {20 cm} (-4.5,5);
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-4.2,0) -- node[below] {40 cm} (4.2,0);
    
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
             </statement>
             <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_ck2kgyqz">
                    Complete the cone from which the bucket is made, by adding a smaller cone of height <m>x </m>cm.
                </p>
                              <image width="40%">

                <latex-image label="galvanised-frustum">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Define a light purple color
                        \definecolor{lightpurple}{RGB}{230,230,250}
                        
                        % Bottom ellipse (wider)
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) ellipse (3 and 1.5);
                        \fill[lightpurple, opacity=0.7] (0,0) ellipse (3 and 1.5);
                        
                        % Top ellipse (narrower)
                        \draw[thick] (0,5) ellipse (1.5 and 0.75);
                        \fill[lightpurple, opacity=0.7] (0,5) ellipse (1.5 and 0.75);
                        
                        % Side surfaces
                        \fill[lightpurple, opacity=0.5] 
                            (-3,0) -- (-1.5,5) -- (1.5,5) -- (3,0) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Outline of side lines
                        \draw[thick] (-3,0) -- (-1.5,5);
                        \draw[thick] (3,0) -- (1.5,5);
                        \draw[thick] (-3,0) -- (3,0);
                        \draw[thick] (-1.5,5) -- (1.5,5);
                        \draw[dashed] (-1.5,5) --(0,8);
                        \draw[dashed] (1.5,5) --(0,8);
                        \draw[dashed] (0,5) --(0,8);                       
                        % Height line (dashed)
                        \draw[dashed, blue] (0,0) -- (0,8);
                        <!-- \draw[circle] (8.0); -->
                        % Dimension lines and labels
                        \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-3.5,0) -- node[left] {20 cm} (-3.5,5);
                        \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-3,0) -- node[below] {40 cm} (3,0);
                        \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (2,5) -- node[left] {x cm} (2,8);
                        \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-1.5,5) -- node[above] {30 cm} (1.5,5);

                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p xml:id="auto_vs33sglp">
                    From the cocept of similarity and enlargement;
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ax6rl18f">
                    <m>\frac{R}{r} = \frac{H}{h}</m> and <m>\frac{H-h}{R-r} = \frac{h}{r}</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ysbe0wal">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\frac{x}{15} = \amp\frac {x + 20 \text{cm} }{20 \text{cm}}</mrow>
                        <mrow> 20 x  = \amp 15x \text{cm} + 300 \text{cm}</mrow>
                        <mrow>300 \text{cm} = \amp  20 x -  15 x  </mrow>
                        <mrow> 300 \text{cm} = \amp 5x</mrow>
                        <mrow>60 \text{cm} = \amp x</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ll0potfh">
                    Surface area of a frustrum = Area of curved surface of bigger cone - Area of curved surface of snaller cone
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_fdszqrx0">
                    <m>\pi RL - \pi rl</m>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \text{Surface area (Large)} = \amp \frac {22}{7} \times 20 \text{cm} \times \sqrt{80^2 + 20^2} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 5183.33 \text{cm}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \text{Surface area (small)} = \amp \frac {22}{7} \times 15 \text{cm} \times \sqrt{60^2 + 15^2} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 2915.62 \text{cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Differences in the Surface areas} = \amp 5183.33 \text{cm} - 2915.62 \text{cm}</mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 2267.71 \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
             </solution>
             </example>

             <example xml:id="auto_4eueqr2h">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ieihhgon">
                        A bucket is in the shape of a frustum of a cone. The top radius is 
                        <m>14</m> cm, the bottom radius is <m>6</m> cm, and the vertical 
                        height of the bucket is <m>24</m> cm.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_qbpe4a4b">
                        Find the total surface area of the bucket (Take <m>\pi = 3.142</m>). 
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p xml:id="auto_cx6ujdy8">
                        <ol marker="Step 1:">
                            <li xml:id="auto_11q670vj">
                                <p xml:id="auto_4w4utrtt">
                                    Use similarity to find the heights of the two cones.
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_l9ad0yoi">
                                    Let the height of the large cone be <m>H</m> and the height of the small cone be <m>h</m>.
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_lab6hzum">
                                    From similarity:
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_t6drzqql">
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow>\frac{H}{h} = \frac{R}{r}\amp </mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp \frac{14}{6}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp \frac{7}{3}</mrow>
                                    </md>
                                    
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_u9wi6lky">
                                    So, <m>H = \frac{7}{3}h</m>
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_9gs6hsxg">
                                    Since the frustum height is 24 cm:
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_86f4ivhz">
                                    <m>H - h = 24</m>
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_pcpxm1se">
                                    <m>\frac{7}{3}h - h = 24</m>
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_l3fqcbvo">
                                    <m>\frac{4}{3}h = 24</m>
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_chwhmxbs">
                                    <m>h = 18 \;\text{ cm}</m>
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_b5xiigjm">
                                    Therefore: <m>H = 42 \;\text{ cm}</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_xrwww8qm">
                                <p xml:id="auto_749i061c">
                                   Find slant heights. 
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_ffe8lxcp">
                                    Large cone:
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_72jj3w0c">
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow> L = \amp \sqrt{42^2 + 14^2}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{1764 + 196}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{1960}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp 44.29 \;\text{ cm}</mrow>
                                    </md>
                                    
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_u7uy1q7d">
                                    Small cone:
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_ovzx4mfd">
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow> l = \amp \sqrt{18^2 + 6^2}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{324 + 36}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{360}</mrow>
                                        <mrow> = \amp 18.97 \;\text{ cm}</mrow>
                                    </md>
                                    
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_3b5ybw10">
                                <p xml:id="auto_a16q1d12">
                                    Curved surface areas.
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_4w4m19fz">
                                    Large cone:
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_6kzmi8wg">
                                   <m>\pi R L = 3.142 \times 14 \times 44.29 = 1948.7 \;\text{ cm}^2</m> 
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_50p6wxhg">
                                   Small cone: 
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_mptabqbq">
                                    <m>\pi r l = 3.142 \times 6 \times 18.97 = 357.6 \text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_l5gnac0p">
                                    Curved surface area of frustum:
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_v60f8zdk">
                                    <m>1948.7 - 357.6 = 1591.1 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_1evgycmq">
                                <p xml:id="auto_g19xyrkb">
                                    Add area of the base.
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_q6fzgld0">
                                    <m>\pi r^2 = 3.142 \times 6^2 = 113.1 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_uy8t0x7t">
                                    Total Surface Area:
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_bfe908ho">
                                    <m>1591.1 + 113.1 = 1704.2 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </solution>
             </example>

             <example xml:id="auto_814av8kf">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_75qk84sx">
                        A container is in the shape of a frustum of a rectangular pyramid. The bottom base measures <m>20 \text{ cm} \times 12 \text{ cm}</m>, the top base measures <m>10 \text{ cm} \times 6 \text{ cm}</m>, and the vertical height is <m>15 \text{ cm}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_9oq7czmu">
                        Find the total surface area of the frustum.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p xml:id="auto_a8sx9q6x">
                        <ol marker="Step 1:">
                            <li xml:id="auto_24h0yhte">
                                <p xml:id="auto_b40w0le8">
                                    Find the slant heights.
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_p31ek93s">
                                    Difference in lengths:
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_4uv4pymj">
                                    <m>\frac{20 - 10}{2} = 5 \;\text{ cm}</m>
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_97902ev8">
                                    Slant height (length direction):
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_88nqjqy2">
                                   <md>
                                    <mrow> \text{Slant height (length direction)} = \amp \sqrt{15^2 + 5^2}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{225 + 25}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{250}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp 15.81 \;\text{ cm}</mrow>
                                   </md>
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_d6v16u7y">
                                    Difference in widths:
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_p9uoe5oq">
                                    <m>\frac{12 - 6}{2} = 3 \text{ cm}</m>
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_ijrhiiie">
                                    <md>
                                    <mrow> \text{Slant height (width direction)} = \amp \sqrt{15^2 + 3^2}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{225 + 9}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{234}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> = \amp 15.33 \;\text{ cm}</mrow>
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_4q8vi0ng">
                                <p xml:id="auto_hbvxo2w4">
                                    Find areas of trapezoidal faces. Two faces with parallel sides 20 cm and 10 cm:
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_d3jiocr5">
                                    <m>\frac{1}{2}(20 + 10)(15.81) = 237.15 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_6k4lf1gx">
                                    Total for both is <m>2 \times 237.15 = 474.3 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_a1i7j677">
                                    Two faces with parallel sides 12 cm and 6 cm:
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_yaplt0ut">
                                    <m>\frac{1}{2}(12 + 6)(15.33) = 137.97 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_4zsr5lh1">
                                    Total for both is <m>2 \times 137.97 = 275.94 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_andmbk10">
                                <p xml:id="auto_xgeeuue2">
                                    Add base areas.
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_3shpcrtn">
                                    Bottom base area is <m>20 \times 12 = 240 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_53p8a3v5">
                                    Top base area is <m>10 \times 6 = 60 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_icjs6v00">
                                <p xml:id="auto_h2jtmmev">
                                    Total Surface Area.
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_h466cqz0">
                                    <m>474.3 + 275.94 + 240 + 60 = 1050.24 \;\text{ cm}^2</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </solution>
             </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_56j9j2sg">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 5 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_1d6278oi">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Individual
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_tfp16g9w">
            <alert>Exit Ticket:</alert> Students complete the following questions individually.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_c44h7jn1">
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li xml:id="auto_6oizcdrb">
                    <p xml:id="auto_276ioo3n">A frustum of a square pyramid has top side length <m>4</m> m, bottom side length <m>6</m> m, and slant height <m>5</m> m. Calculate the total surface area.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_acnru633">
                    <p xml:id="auto_n6mcmyz3">A conical frustum has a bottom radius of <m>6</m> cm and a slant height of <m>10</m> cm. (i) Explain the difference between curved surface area and total surface area. (ii) Find only the curved surface area.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ft4dnbl4">
                    <p xml:id="auto_hst03iig">If the curved surface area of a frustum is <m>330 \text{ cm}^2</m>, the top radius is <m>5</m> cm, and the bottom radius is <m>10</m> cm, find the slant height.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_wuc59s2r">
            <alert>Answer Key (Teacher Reference):</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_166yvzfa">
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li xml:id="auto_1j11xdm8">
                    <p xml:id="auto_kzsonmv8">Lateral <m>= \frac{1}{2}(16 + 24) \times 5 = 100 \text{ m}^2</m>. Base areas <m>= 16 + 36 = 52 \text{ m}^2</m>. Total <m>= 152 \text{ m}^2</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_xa0r1itn">
                    <p xml:id="auto_za1bzfdy">(i) CSA is only the side surface; TSA includes CSA plus both circular bases. (ii) CSA <m>= \pi \times 6 \times 10 = 188.50 \text{ cm}^2</m>.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_xiryl8nk">
                    <p xml:id="auto_6g36nsml"><m>330 = 3.14 \times (10 + 5) \times \ell</m>, so <m>\ell = 330 \div 47.1 = 7</m> cm.</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A frustum of a square pyramid has a top square side of length <m>4</m> m, a bottom square side of length <m>6</m> m, and a slant height (along one face) of length <m>5</m>. Calculate the total surface area of the frustum.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Area of the top square : <m>4^2 = 16</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Area of the bottom square: <m>6^2 = 36</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Area of the trapezoidal faces: <m> \frac{1}{2} \times (4+6)\times 5 = 25</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total surface area: <m> 16 + 36 + 4 \times 25 = 152</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Total surface area <m>= 152\; \text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A conical frustum has a bottom radius of <m>6</m> cm, no top (the top is flat), and a slant height of <m>10</m> cm. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(i)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Explain the difference between the curved surface area and the total surface area of a frustum.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Find only the curved surface area of the frustum.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(i)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                             The curved surface area of a frustum is the area of only the slanted side surface. The total surface area is the curved surface area plus the areas of the top and bottom circular bases.   
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>188.4 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A frustum is formed by cutting a cone with a height of <m>24</m> cm into two parts. The smaller cone has a height of <m>9</m> cm. If the base radius of the original cone is <m>16</m> cm, calculate the total surface area of the frustum.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>2162.1 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    If the curved surface area of a frustum is <m>330 {\;\textcm}^2</m>, the top radius is <m>5</m> cm, and the bottom radius is <m>10</m> cm, find the slant height of the frustum.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Slant height <m>\approx 7\; \text{cm}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>
            <exercise  label="ex-calculating-the-lateral-surface-area-of-a-frustum-of-a-square-py">
                <stack label="stk-calculating-the-lateral-surface-area-of-a-frustum-of-a-square-py" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-7-Surface-Area-and-Volume-of-Solids/2-7-8-Surface-area-of-a-Frustum/Calculating-the-Lateral-Surface-Area-of-a-Frustum-of-a-Square-Py.xml" />
            </exercise>
                
