            <exercise  label="ex-calculating-the-volume-of-a-cuboid">
                <stack label="stk-calculating-the-volume-of-a-cuboid" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-7-Surface-Area-and-Volume-of-Solids/2-7-8-Surface-area-of-a-Frustum/Calculating-the-Volume-of-a-cuboid.xml" />
            </exercise> -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_3bie2tq6">
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_y8x2q99j"><p xml:id="auto_asng6s1v">Provide pre-cut frustum models for students to measure.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_4t14yh1l"><p xml:id="auto_sbi1yw6a">Use frustums with simple dimensions for initial practice.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ce3cdfeq"><p xml:id="auto_7ka5hfpo">Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_gaiwoxp5"><p xml:id="auto_99afwm02">Break down the formula into steps: find bottom base area, find top base area, find curved surface area, add.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_gq7ryosi"><p xml:id="auto_xfcx6ukb">Allow use of calculators.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_4ellkoqv">
            <alert>For On-Level Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_odyn482f"><p xml:id="auto_qa8uef0u">Encourage students to verify their formula with different frustum dimensions.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_8hqd03v4"><p xml:id="auto_ujzqcsi1">Provide mixed practice with frustums with and without top bases.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_khb89jrh"><p xml:id="auto_zgvt20vq">Challenge students to find the surface area when only height and radii are given.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_fvrk2u8q">
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_h6rd5r7e"><p xml:id="auto_o3s6rjxn">Challenge students to derive the formula using similarity and enlargement.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zyqyttp5"><p xml:id="auto_k5lnyj23">Explore real-world applications: lampshades, buckets, cooling towers, tunnels.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_g37ewuoi"><p xml:id="auto_dy99xyk6">Investigate problems where the slant height must be calculated using the Pythagorean theorem.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_kxfh6euz"><p xml:id="auto_jdk0pjht">Apply the concept to composite solids involving frustums.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_kx6opvjm"><p xml:id="auto_oox24zhn">Solve optimisation problems: given a fixed surface area, what dimensions maximise the volume?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Extension Activity</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_1az9m1ni">
            <alert>Real-World Application: Designing Frustum Cups</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_o37pbmeg">
            Work in groups. Design your own frustum cups with chosen dimensions for a school event.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_wb317agl">
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_m3hiello"><p xml:id="auto_h6netj8p">Choose dimensions for your frustum cup (top radius, bottom radius, slant height).</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_etvwej3b"><p xml:id="auto_c8vwl24f">Calculate the surface area of your cup using the frustum formula.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_olv4fa81"><p xml:id="auto_x91oanyk">Determine how much material (paper or plastic) is needed to make 100 cups.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_dzoyj6bu"><p xml:id="auto_xsy28qjy">If material costs Ksh 2 per square cm, calculate the total cost.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jll1u0pq"><p xml:id="auto_id7lwa7y">Compare your design with classmates and discuss which design is most cost-effective.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

